# Coding Standards

These standards define how code should be written throughout the project.

Always prioritize readability, consistency, maintainability, and simplicity.

---

# General Principles

Write code that another developer can understand quickly.

Prefer:

- Simple
- Explicit
- Predictable
- Reusable

Avoid:

- Clever code
- Premature optimization
- Deep nesting
- Unnecessary abstraction

---

# TypeScript

Always use TypeScript.

Do not use:

- any
- @ts-ignore
- type assertions unless absolutely necessary

Prefer inference when obvious.

Create explicit interfaces when data is shared across components.

---

# Naming

Use clear, descriptive names.

Examples:

Component

InvitationCard

Hook

useCountdown

Utility

formatWeddingDate

Constant

MAX_GUESTS

Boolean

isOpen

hasResponded

canSubmit

Avoid abbreviations unless universally understood.

---

# Components

Each component should have a single responsibility.

Prefer:

One component
One purpose

If a component exceeds roughly 200 lines, consider splitting it into smaller components.

---

# Props

Use interfaces for component props.

Example:

interface InvitationCardProps {
  title: string;
  subtitle?: string;
}

Keep props minimal.

Avoid prop drilling when a better composition exists.

---

# Functions

Functions should:

- Do one thing.
- Have descriptive names.
- Return early when possible.
- Avoid deeply nested conditions.

Prefer small helper functions over long functions.

---

# Imports

Group imports in this order:

1. React / Next.js
2. Third-party packages
3. Internal aliases
4. Relative imports

Remove unused imports.

Prefer project aliases over long relative paths when configured.

---

# File Organization

Within a file, organize in this order:

1. Imports
2. Types / Interfaces
3. Constants
4. Component
5. Helper functions (if private)

---

# Comments

Code should be self-explanatory.

Only write comments when explaining:

- Why something exists.
- Business rules.
- Non-obvious decisions.

Avoid comments that describe what the code already says.

---

# Error Handling

Never silently ignore errors.

Provide meaningful error messages.

Fail gracefully.

---

# Constants

Avoid magic numbers and hard-coded strings.

Extract reusable values into constants.

Example:

const RSVP_DEADLINE = ...

---

# Duplication

Before writing new code:

Search for an existing implementation.

Prefer:

Reuse

over

Rewrite.

---

# Accessibility

Do not sacrifice accessibility for convenience.

Semantic HTML is preferred over div-based layouts.

---

# Responsive Design

All UI must work on:

- Mobile
- Tablet
- Desktop

Use mobile-first development.

---

# Performance

Avoid unnecessary:

- Re-renders
- State
- Effects

Keep components as lightweight as possible.

---

# Git Hygiene

Generate focused changes.

Do not modify unrelated files.

Do not introduce unrelated refactors while implementing a feature.

---

# Definition of Done

Code is complete when it is:

- Readable
- Typed
- Reusable
- Responsive
- Accessible
- Production-ready